<subSubSection id="2FD69A874B1F8BA026816FD01A4A8DA6" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="30D58E9A81F4D8D4B8C98FF51E40F0A6" pageNumber="218">
etymology L 
<taxonomicName id="B723DFF3DD4A805D2FE5BCC503B333B6" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33945" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole pubiventris Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubiventris">pubiventris</taxonomicName>
, hairy belly, evidently alluding to the conspicuously long pilosity of the gaster.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="614E1DF9A1B77022607AF23C930DA119" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="6EF9CC3977FAD825ACEDC986B24E17CF" pageNumber="218">
Diagnosis A medium-sized brown member of the 
<taxonomicName id="EB7F38B05537BE904BC245D923272D58" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142247" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atta" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Atta diligens Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diligens">diligens</taxonomicName>
group with relatively sparse, extremely long, erect to suberect curving
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0655BF7C2934F36B304AD73F43A27F95" type="description">
<paragraph id="923B9CF6DB9E94F1AE8AD4377A4087D3" pageNumber="218">hairs over the dorsa of the head and body.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E427AF24615495873370EB4336A77FF6" pageNumber="218">Major: sculpturing of head consists entirely of carinulae, which are confined to the anterior half of the head capsule; promesonotal profile trilobous and pronotal humerus subangulate in dorsal-oblique view. Minor: humerus angulate; pronotum mostly foveolate and opaque.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8AF7C79AF2ADF45FAA464D57AFD02AC7" pageNumber="218">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="98EB6EBCABC899B66869922AC8B5906C" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181681" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole longiseta Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longiseta">longiseta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="77D939611FE607BAB8489770C48BFFFE" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33999" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole sensitiva Borgmeier" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sensitiva">sensitiva</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="813411DBA8B951185CA4DBF3B377E743" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181704" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole variegata Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">variegata</taxonomicName>
; differing in many details of body form, sculpturing, and pilosity, as illustrated. See also the less similar 
<taxonomicName id="D2C815697AC60626A5141794C0D15192" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33625" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole blumenauensis Kempf" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blumenauensis">blumenauensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="1944E701C7C209B7ECCC112BCBDF1ED4" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181680" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole rochai Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rochai">rochai</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4983988B77F47E939CACF351F42143AE" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33996" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole seeldrayersi Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seeldrayersi">seeldrayersi</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="819B8B7743A03E8A0993A1090215A3CD" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34079" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole vafra Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vafra">vafra</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8AB0E9BD35708C3BC7EBCB51D5885754" pageNumber="218">Majors from Colombia have shorter pilosity and more angulate humeri than the Brazilian series; and thus may represent a distinct species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4899839DEE5F0714D8BC89342696C71" pageNumber="218">Measurements (mm) Syntype major (Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard): HW 1.14, HL 1.12, SL 0.86, EL 0.22, PW 0.56.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="03EEC375C7CB7428FACE6EFF05197617" pageNumber="218">Syntype minor (Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard): HW 0.54, HL 0.68, SL 0.86, EL 0.16, PW 0.40.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ECC267D0E1ACA83AE3F572C2B74978D9" pageNumber="218">Color Major: light reddish yellow (probably a callow or faded; fresher specimens are blackish brown).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="10E8760A08532BAFF3CC0928EE5706E7" pageNumber="218">Minor: body medium brown, with light brown appendages (fresher specimens are blackish brown).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BCEB7538D846A1A84092D19EEC2E9C37" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="1B66C316644B47FAAC26459B8BAE8BCA" pageNumber="218">Range Santa Catarina, Sao Paulo, and Ceara, Brazil; and Magdalena, Colombia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5834D3C192F09F6A2876306751920F19" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2C6111D72D16D6863938EFCECAE248A5" pageNumber="218">biology The localities, combined with a note accompanying a specimen from El Campano, Magdalena, Colombia (&quot;in road,&quot; W. L. Brown), suggests that this species may be adapted to disturbed habitats. A winged queen was collected at El Campano in June.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
